					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-JH"/>, Section 3.1, Exercise 3.1.1.) </p></aside>
							Find the vector equation for the line through <m>(-7,6,0)</m> and <m>(-1,1,4)</m>.  Then, find the parametric equations for this line.
						</statement>
						<hint>
							The <em>vector equation</em> of a line <m>\ell</m> through points <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is given by
							<me>
								\vec{x}
								=
								\vect{OP}
								+
								t
								\vect{PQ}
								.
							</me>
						</hint>
						<hint>
							The <em>parametric equations</em> of a line <m>\ell</m> are the equations for each of the coordinates in the vector equation.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							The vector equation of the line is given by 
							<me>
								\vec{x} 
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} -7\\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								+
								t
								\left(
									\begin{bmatrix} -1\\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
									-
									\begin{bmatrix} -7\\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								\right)
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} -7\\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								+
								t
								\begin{bmatrix} 6\\ -5 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
								.
							</me>
							To check that we did not make a mistake: for <m>t=0</m>, we are indeed at the point <m>(-7,6,0)</m>, and for <m>t=1</m>, we are at the point
							<me>
								\begin{bmatrix} -7\\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								+
								\begin{bmatrix} 6\\ -5 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} -1\\ 1 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} ,
							</me>
							the second point.

							For the parametric equations, we just have to rephrase the above vector equation in terms of its coordinates:
							<me>
								x_1 = -7 + 6t
								;
								x_2 = 6 - 5t
								;
								x_3 = 4t
								.
							</me>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							The vector equation is given by
							<me>
								\vec{x} 
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} -7\\ 6 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								+
								t
								\begin{bmatrix} 6\\ -5 \\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
								,
							</me>
							and the parametric equations by
							<me>
								x_1 = -7 + 6t
								;
								x_2 = 6 - 5t
								;
								x_3 = 4t
								.
							</me>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Adapted from <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 4.1, Exercise 4.1.22.) </p></aside>
							Find the vector <!-- general,--> and parametric form of the following lines:
							<ol marker="[a]"> 
							 	<li><p>The line parallel to <m>\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} </m> and passing through <m>P=(1,-1,3)</m>.</p>
							 	<p>
