							 	<li>
							 		<p>The line passing through <m>P=(1,0,-3)</m> and parallel to the line with parametric equations <m>x_1 = -1 +2t</m>, <m>x_2 = 2-t</m>, and <m>x_3= 3+3t</m>.</p>
							 		<p>
								 	<!-- <hint>
									</hint> -->
							 		<solution>
								 		<p>
								 			First, let us find a directional vector for the line whose parametric equations are given. For <m>t=0</m>, that line passes through the point <m>Q=(-1,2,3)</m> and for <m>t=1</m>, it passes through <m>R=(1,1,6)</m>. Therefore, the vector
								 		</p>
								 			<p><me>
								 				\vect{QR}=
								 				\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				1-(-1) \\ 1-2 \\ 6-3
										 		\end{bmatrix} 
										 		=
										 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				2 \\ -1 \\ 3
										 		\end{bmatrix} 			 		
										 	</me></p>
										<p>gives the direction of said line.</p>
								 		<p>The vector equation of the line in question is therefore given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			1 \\ 0\\ -3
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 3
									 		\end{bmatrix} ,
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>
									 	because for <m>t=0</m>, it passes through <m>P</m>, and it has the perscribed directional vector.</p>
									 	<p>The parametric form is then given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = -t
											;
											x_3 = -3+3t
											.
										</me>
										</p>
								 	</solution>
								 	<answer>
								 		<p>Vector equation:</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			1 \\ 0\\ -3
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 3
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Parametric form:</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = -t
											;
											x_3 = -3+3t.
										</me>
										</p>
									</answer>
								</p>
							 	</li>
							 	<li>
							 		<p>The line passing through <m>P=(2,-1,1)</m> and parallel to the line with parametric equations <m>x_1 =2-t</m>, <m>x_2 =1</m> and <m>x_3 = t</m>.</p>
							 		<p>
								 	<!-- <hint>
									</hint> -->
							 		<solution>
								 		<p>
								 			First, let us find a directional vector for the line whose parametric equations are given. For <m>t=0</m>, that line passes through the point <m>Q=(2,1,0)</m> and for <m>t=1</m>, it passes through <m>R=(1,1,1)</m>. Therefore, the vector
								 		</p>
								 			<p><me>
								 				\vect{QR}=
								 				\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				1-2 \\ 1-1 \\ 1-0
										 		\end{bmatrix} 
										 		=
										 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
										 		\end{bmatrix} 			 		
										 	</me></p>
										<p>gives the direction of said line.</p>
								 		<p>The vector equation of the line in question is therefore given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>The parametric form is therefore given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 2-t
											;
											x_2 = -1
											;
											x_3 = 1+t
											.
										</me>
										</p>
								 	</solution>
								 	<answer>
								 		<p>Vector equation:</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			2 \\ -1 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
									 			-1 \\ 0 \\ 1
									 		\end{bmatrix} 
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Parametric form:</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 2-t
											;
