								</p>
							 	</li>
							 	<li>
							 		<p>The lines through <m>P=(1,0,1)</m> that meet the line <m>\ell</m> whose vector equation is given by <m>\mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}  +t \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} </m> at points with distance 3 from <m>Q=(1,2,0)</m>.</p>
							 		<p>
								 	<!-- <hint>
									</hint> -->
							 		<solution>
								 		<p>First, let us find the points <m>R</m> on <m>\ell</m> that have distance <m>3</m> from <m>Q</m>: Having distance <m>3</m> means exactly that
								 		</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\norm{ \vect{QR} } = 3.
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>The fact that <m>R</m> is on <m>\ell</m> means that, for some real number <m>t</m>, we have</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\vect{OR} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			+
								 			t
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>Thus,</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\vect{QR} = 
								 			\left(
									 			\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
									 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 			+
									 			t
									 			\begin{bmatrix} 
									 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
									 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			\right)
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1\\2\\0
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2t \\ -t\\ 2t
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>and we therefore want</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\norm{ \begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2t \\ -t\\ 2t
								 			\end{bmatrix} } = 3,
								 			\text{ i.e. }
								 			(2t)^2 + (-t)^2 + (2t)^2 = 9.
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>This means, we need <m>9t^2=9</m>, or in other words, <m>t=\pm 1</m>. Therefore, there are two points <m>R_+, R_-</m> on <m>\ell</m> which have distance <m>3</m> from <m>Q</m>, namely the points that satisfy</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\vect{O R_+} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			+
								 			1
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				3 \\ 1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>and</p>
								 		<p><me>
								 			\vect{OR_-} = 
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 2\\ 0
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			1
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ -1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-1 \\ 3\\ -2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			.
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>Any line through <m>P</m> can be described by the vector equation </p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\vect{OP}
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\vec{d}
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>for some directional vector <m>\vec{d}</m>. For our line to go through <m>R_+</m>, we need to choose</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{d}
									 		=
									 		\vect{PR_+}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				3 \\ 1\\ 2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>and the vector equation for this line is then given by </p>
								 		<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			.
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Its parametric form is therefore given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1+2s
											;
											x_2 = s
											;
											x_3 = 1+s
											.
										</me>
										</p>
									 	<p>For the line to go through <m>R_-</m> on the other hand, we need to choose</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{d}
									 		=
									 		\vect{PR_-}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-1 \\ 3\\ -2
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			-
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
								 			=
								 			\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 		</me></p>
								 		<p>and the vector equation for this line is then given by </p>
								 		<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		s
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
								 			.
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Its parametric form is then given by</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1-2s
											;
											x_2 = 3s
											;
											x_3 = 1-3s
											.
										</me>
										</p>
								 	</solution>
								 	<answer>
								 		There are two lines that meet the given line at distance <m>3</m> from <m>Q</m> and go through <m>P</m>:
								 		<p>Vector equation of the first line:</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				2 \\ 1\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix}
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Parametric form of the first line:</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1+2t
											;
											x_2 = t
											;
											x_3 = 1+t
										</me>
										</p>
										<p>Vector equation of the second line:</p>
									 	<p><me>
									 		\vec{x}
									 		=
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				1 \\ 0\\ 1
								 			\end{bmatrix} 
									 		+
									 		t
									 		\begin{bmatrix} 
								 				-2 \\ 3\\ -3
								 			\end{bmatrix}
									 	</me></p>
									 	<p>Parametric form of the second line:</p>
									 	<p><me>
											x_1 = 1-2t
											;
											x_2 = 3t
											;
											x_3 = 1-3t
											.
										</me>
										</p>
									</answer>
								</p>
							 	</li>
							</ol>
						</statement>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.14.) </p></aside>
							Find the normal, general, and vector form of each of the following planes.					
						<hint xml:id="hint-what-is-needed-for-normal-form">
							In order to determine the <em>normal form</em> of a plane, you need both a single point <m>P</m> on the plane and a normal vector <m>\vec{n}</m> to the plane.  See <xref ref="def-normal-form-plane" />.
						</hint>
					 	 <ol marker="[a]"> 
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Passing through <m>A=(2,1,3)</m>,  <m>B=(1,1,3)</m>, and <m>C=(1,2,-3)</m>.</p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					<p>We begin by finding two direction vectors for this plane, namely <m>\vec{d_1} = \vec{AB} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec{d_2} = \vec{AC} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-6\end{bmatrix}</m>.  We can then use any point on the plane to give a vector equation, such as this one:
					 					<me>\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\3\end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix}+s\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-6\end{bmatrix}</me>.
					 					</p>
					 					<p>To find the normal form we need a normal vector, that is, a vector <m>\vec{n}</m> such that <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_1} = 0</m> and <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} = 0</m>.  If you are comfortable with the cross product, one solution is to take <m>\vec{n} = \vec{d_1} \times \vec{d_2}</m>.  
					 					We are not teaching the cross product in this course, so we will find <m>\vec{n}</m> another way.  Suppose that <m>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Then we need:
					 					<me>0 = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_1} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\end{bmatrix} \cdot\begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix} = -a</me>
					 					<me>0 = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-6\end{bmatrix} = -a+b-6c</me>.
					 					We have here a system of two linear equations in three variables, and any solution to the system will give us a normal vector.  Solving the system using our usual techniques, we find that <m>a=0, b=6, c=1</m> is a solution, so we take <m>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\6\\1\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Then if we use the point <m>A</m> to define our normal equation, we get
					 					<me>\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}0\\6\\1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\3\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}0\\6\\1\end{bmatrix}</me>.
					 					</p>
					 					<p>Finally, to find the general equation we just calculate the dot products in the normal equation, and get
					 					<me>6y+z = 9</me>.</p>
					 				</solution>
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
					 					\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}0\\6\\1\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\3\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}0\\6\\1\end{bmatrix}
					 					</me>(Other answers are possible).</p>
					 					<p>General form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
					 						6y+z=9
					 					</me>
					 					(Every correct answer is a non-zero multiple of this one).</p>
					 					<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}2\\1\\3\end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}-1\\0\\0\end{bmatrix}+s\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-6\end{bmatrix}
										</me>
										(Many other correct answers are also possible).
										</p>					 					
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Passing through <m>A=(1,-1,6)</m>, <m>B=(0,0,1)</m>, and <m>C=(4,7,-11)</m>.</p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					<p>
					 						We follow the same strategy as in the previous example.  As direction vectors we take <m>\vec{d_1} = \vec{AB} = \begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-5\end{bmatrix}</m> and <m>\vec{d_2} = \vec{BC} = \begin{bmatrix}4\\7\\-12\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Then, using the point <m>B</m> this time as our chosen point on the plane, we get a vector equation:
					 						<me>\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-5\end{bmatrix} + s\begin{bmatrix}4\\7\\-12\end{bmatrix}</me>.
					 					</p>
					 					<p>To find a normal vector, let <m>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Then we need:
					 					<me>0 = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_1} = -a+b-5c</me>
					 					<me>0 = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} = 4a+7b-12c</me>.
					 					One solution to this system is <m>a=23, b=-32, c=-11</m>, so we take <m>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}23\\-32\\-11\end{bmatrix}</m>.  Using the point <m>B</m>, our normal form equation is:
					 					<me>\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}23\\-32\\-11\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}23\\-32\\-11\end{bmatrix}</me>.
					 					</p>
					 					<p>Finally, expanding the dot products above gives us the general equation:
					 					<me>23x-32y-11z = -11</me>.</p>
					 				</solution>
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
					 						\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}23\\-32\\-11\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix}\cdot\begin{bmatrix}23\\-32\\-11\end{bmatrix}
					 					</me></p>
					 					<p>General form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											23x-32y-11z = -11
					 					</me></p>
					 					<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\\z\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}0\\0\\1\end{bmatrix} + t\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\\-5\end{bmatrix} + s\begin{bmatrix}4\\7\\-12\end{bmatrix}
										</me>
										</p>					 					
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Passing through <m>P=(2,-3,5)</m> and parallel to the plane with general equation <m>3x_1-2x_2-x_3=0</m>.</p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					Two planes are parallel if and only if they have the same normal vectors. Therefore, we should first find a  normal vector to the plane whose general equation is given: If we chose
					 					<p><me>
					 						\vec{n}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix},
										</me></p>
										then the given general form is equivalent to
										<p><me>
					 						\vec{n}
					 						\cdot\vec{x}
					 						=0,
										</me></p>
										so <m>\vec{n}</m> is indeed a normal vector. With this at hand, any point <m>X=(x_1,x_2,x_3)</m> on the plane whose normal form we are after can be described by <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m>, or more explicitly:
										<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 2 \\
												 - 3 \\
												 5
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										</me></p>
										To get the general form, we have to compute the dot product on the left-hand side and rearrange:
										<p><me>
											3x_{1} - 2 x_{2} - x_{3}							
											= 7.
										</me></p>
										For the vector form, we need two <em>non-parallel</em> vectors <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>\vec{v}</m> which are orthogonal to <m>\vec{n}</m>, i.e. they need to satisfy
										<p><me>
											\vec{u}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
											\text{ and }
											\vec{v}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0.
										</me></p>
										For example,
										<p><me>
											\vec{u}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 -2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\text{ and }
											\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 3 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
										work. Therefore, the vector equation of the plane is
										<p><me>
											\vec{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\vec{u}
											+s\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2\\-3\\5
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 -2
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 3 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me>.</p>
					 				</solution>
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 -2 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 x_1 \\
											 x_2 \\
											 x_3
											\end{bmatrix}=
											7
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											3x_{1} - 2 x_{2} - x_{3}							
											= 7
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
\vec{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\vec{u}
											+s\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2\\-3\\5
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 -2
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 3 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Passing through <m>P=(3,0,-1)</m> and parallel to the plane with equation <m>2x_1-x_2+x_3=3</m>.</p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					Two planes are parallel if and only if they have the same normal vectors. Therefore, we should first find a  normal vector to the plane whose general equation is given: If we chose
					 					<p><me>
					 						\vec{n}
					 						=
					 						\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix},
										</me></p>
										then the given general form is equivalent to
										<p><me>
					 						\vec{n}
					 						\cdot\vec{x}
					 						=3,
										</me></p>
										so <m>\vec{n}</m> is indeed a normal vector. With this at hand, any point <m>X=(x_1,x_2,x_3)</m> on the plane whose normal form we are after can be described by <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m>, or more explicitly:
										<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										</me></p>
										To get the general form, we have to compute the dot product on the left-hand side and rearrange:
										<p><me>
											2x_{1} - x_{2} + x_{3}							
											= 5.
										</me></p>
										For the vector form, we need two <em>non-parallel</em> vectors <m>\vec{u}</m>, <m>\vec{v}</m> which are orthogonal to <m>\vec{n}</m>, i.e. they need to satisfy
										<p><me>
											\vec{u}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
											\text{ and }
											\vec{v}\cdot \begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0.
										</me></p>
										For example,
										<p><me>
											\vec{u}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\text{ and }
											\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 1 \\
											 2 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
										work. Therefore, the vector equation of the plane is
										<p><me>
											\vec{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\vec{u}
											+s\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 0 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 1 \\
											 2 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me>.</p>
					 				</solution>
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 2 \\
											 -1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=0
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											2x_{1} - x_{2} + x_{3}							
											= 5
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
\vec{x}
											=
											\vect{OP}
											+t\vec{u}
											+s\vec{v}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
											 3 \\
											 0 \\
											 -1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+t\begin{bmatrix}
											 0 \\
											 1 \\
											 1
											\end{bmatrix}
											+s\begin{bmatrix}
											 1 \\
											 2 \\
											 0
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Containing <m>P=(3,0,-1)</m> and the line 
					 			<me>
					 				\vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} 
					 			</me>
					 			</p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					Since the plane contains the line, it in particular contains the point <m>Q=(0,0,2)</m> (choose <m>t=0</m> in the line equation). Since <m>P</m> is assumed to be in the plane, we conclude that the line that goes through <m>Q=(0,0,2)</m> and <m>P</m>, whose vector form is given by
										<p><me>
							 				\vec{x}  =
							 				\vect{OQ}
							 				+
							 				s\vect{QP}
							 				= 
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				,
							 			</me></p>
							 			is also contained in the plane. Since this second line's directional vector is not parallel to the first line's directional vector, we conclude that the plane is spanned by those two directional vectors and thus has vector form
					 					<p><me>
							 				\vec{x} 
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							 				+
							 				t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
							 			</me></p>
							 			<p>
										We can find a normal vector <m>\vec{n}</m> by letting <m>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}a\\b\\c\end{bmatrix}</m> and solving the system <m>\vec{n} \cdot \vec{d_1} = 0 = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2}</m>.  We find that a solution is <me>
											\vec{n}
											=			 				
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				.
										</me></p>
										<p>The normal equation of the plane is now given by <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m>, or more explicitly:
										<me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)=0
										</me></p>
										and we get the general form by computing the dot product on the left-hand side and rearranging:
										<p><me>
											6x_2
											=
											0,\text{ i.e. }
											x_2 = 0.
										</me></p>
					 				</solution>	
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					0\\
							 					6 \\
							 					0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\
												 0 \\
												 -1
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)=0
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											x_2 = 0
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
							 				\vec{x} 
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							 				+
							 				t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ -3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
					 		<li>
					 			<p>Containing <m>P=(2,1,0)</m> and the line </p>
						 		<p><me>
						 			\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} 
						 		</me></p>
					 			<p>
					 				<solution>
					 					Since the plane contains the line, it in particular contains the point <m>Q=(3,-1,2)</m> (choose <m>t=0</m> in the line equation). Since <m>P</m> is assumed to be in the plane, we conclude that the line that goes through <m>Q</m> and <m>P</m>, whose vector form is given by
										<p><me>
							 				\vec{x}  =
							 				\vect{OQ}
							 				+
							 				s\vect{QP}
							 				= 
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1 \\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				,
							 			</me></p>
							 			is also contained in the plane. Since this second line's directional vector is not parallel to the first line's directional vector, we conclude that the plane is spanned by those two directional vectors and thus has vector form
					 					<p><me>
							 				\vec{x} 
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							 				+
							 				t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ - 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
							 			</me></p>
										We can find a normal vector <m>\vec{n}</m> by setting <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_1} = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} =0</m> and solving the resulting system.  We find that one solution is
										<p><me>
											\vec{n}=
		
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
												2\\
												3\\
												2
											\end{bmatrix})
							 				.
										</me></p>
										The normal equation of the plane is now given by <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m>, or more explicitly:
										<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					2\\
												3\\
												2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\ -1\\ 2
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)=0
										</me></p>
										and we get the general form by computing the dot product on the left-hand side and rearranging:
										<p><me>
											2x_1 + 3x_2 + 2x_3 
											=
											7.
										</me></p>
					 				</solution>	
					 				<answer>
					 					<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
							 					2\\
												3\\
												2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
												\vec{x}
												-
												\begin{bmatrix}
												 3 \\ -1\\ 2
												\end{bmatrix}
											\right)=0
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											2x_1 + 3x_2 + 2x_3 
											=
											7
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
				 				\vec{x} 
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} 
							 				+
							 				t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ - 1 \end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
					 			</p> 
						 	</li>
						 	<li>
							 	<p>Containing the lines</p>
							 	<p><me>
								 	\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ 1 \end{bmatrix}  \ \text{and} \ \
								 	\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} .
							 	</me></p>
							 	<p>
							 		<solution>
							 			First, we have to find out in which point the two lines meet. (If they do not meet, then they are skew lines since they are clearly not parallel. In this case, they are not in the same plane.) In other words, we are looking for two real numbers <m>s, t</m> such that
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				s
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ 1\\ 1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
										 	\begin{bmatrix}
										 		0 \\ 0\\ 2
										 	\end{bmatrix}
										 	+
										 	t
										 	\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
										 	.
							 			</me>
							 			Componentwise, this vector equation means:
							 			<me>
							 				1 + s = t;\;
							 				-1 + s = -t;\;
							 				2 + s = 2.
							 			</me>
							 			The last equation yields <m>s=0</m> and both other equations then yield <m> t =  1</m>. We conclude that the two lines meet in the point <m>(1,-1,2)</m> because
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				0
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ 1\\ 1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
										 	\begin{bmatrix}
										 		0 \\ 0\\ 2
										 	\end{bmatrix}
										 	+
										 	1
										 	\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
										 	=
										 	\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				.
							 			</me>
							 			Since the two lines are not parallel, their directional vectors span the plane that contains them, so we arrive at the following vector equation of the plane,
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				r
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ 1\\ 1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				q
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				,
							 			</me>
							 			which means in parametric form:
							 			<me>
							 				x_1 = 1 + r + q
							 				;
							 				x_2 = -1 + r - q
							 				;
							 				x_3 = 2 + r
							 				.
							 			</me>
							 			For the normal form, we solve the system <m>\vec{n} \cdot \vec{d_1} = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} = 0</m> and find that we can take
							 			<me>
							 				\vec{n}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
												1\\
												1\\
												-2
											\end{bmatrix}
											.
										</me>
										We now only need a point on the plane, say <m>(1 , -1 ,2)</m>, to give the normal form <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m> explicitly:
										<me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												1\\
												1\\
												-2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\left(
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 - 1\\
												x_2 + 1\\
												x_3 - 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\right)
											=
											0
											.
										</me>
										The general form can then be computed to be:
										<me>
											x_1 + x_2 - 2 x_3
											=
											-4
											.
										</me>
							 		</solution>
							 		<answer>
							 			<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												1\\
												1\\
												-2
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 - 1\\
												x_2 + 1\\
												x_3 - 2
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											x_1 + x_2 - 2 x_3
											=
											-4
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 2
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				r
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ 1\\ 1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				q
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 0
							 				\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
							 	</p>
						 	</li>
						 	<li><p>Containing the lines</p>
							 	<p>	<me>
								 	\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}  \ \text{and} \ \
								 	\vec{x} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -2\\ 5 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} .
							 	</me></p>
							 	<p><solution>
							 			First, we have to find out in which point the two lines meet. (If they do not meet, then they are skew lines since they are clearly not parallel. In this case, they are not in the same plane.) In other words, we are looking for two real numbers <m>s, t</m> such that
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} +s\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				=
										 	\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -2\\ 5 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
										 	.
							 			</me>
							 			Componentwise, this vector equation means:
							 			<me>
							 				3 + s = 2t;\;
							 				1 - s = -2+t;\;
							 				3s = 5 - t.
							 			</me>
							 			The second equation says <m>t=3-s</m>, which we plug into the other equations to get <m>s = 1</m>.

							 			We conclude that the two lines meet in the point <m>(4,0,3)</m> because
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} +1\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				=\begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 0\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
							 				.
							 			</me>
							 			Since the two lines are not parallel, their directional vectors span the plane that contains them, so we arrive at the following vector equation of the plane,
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					4 \\ 0\\ 3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				r
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 3 
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				q
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					2 \\ 1\\ -1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 			</me>.
							 			For the normal form, we again solve the system <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_1} = \vec{n}\cdot\vec{d_2} = 0</m> to find
							 			<me>
							 				\vec{n}
							 				=
							 				
											\begin{bmatrix}
												-2\\
												7\\
												3
											\end{bmatrix}
											.
										</me>
										We now only need a point on the plane, say <m>(4,0,3)</m>, to give the normal form <m>\vec{n}\cdot\vect{PX}=0</m> explicitly:
										<me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												-2\\
												7\\
												3
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 - 4\\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 - 3
											\end{bmatrix}
											.
										</me>
										The general form can then be computed to be:
										<me>
											-2x_1 + 7x_2 + 3 x_3 = 1.
										</me>
							 		</solution>
							 		<answer>
							 			<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												-2\\
												7\\
												3
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 - 4\\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 - 3
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											0
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											-2x_1 + 7x_2 + 3 x_3 = 1
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				=
							 				\begin{bmatrix} 
							 					4 \\ 0\\ 3
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				r
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					1 \\ -1\\ 3 
							 				\end{bmatrix}
							 				+
							 				q
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
							 					2 \\ 1\\ -1
							 				\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
					 				</answer>
					 			</p>
					 		</li>
						 	<li xml:id="subex-plane-equidistant-to-two-points1">
						 		<p>Each point which is equidistant from <m>P=(2,-1,3)</m> and <m>Q=(1,1,-1)</m>.</p>
						 		<p>
							 		<solution>
							 			For a point <m>X</m> to be equidistant from <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, we must have
							 			<me>
							 				\norm{\vect{PX}}= \norm{\vect{QX}}.
							 			</me>
							 			By squaring both sides of the equation, we can rewrite this to
							 			<men xml:id="eq-1">
							 				\vect{PX}\cdot \vect{PX}= \vect{QX}\cdot \vect{QX}.
							 			</men>
							 			If we use that <m>\vect{PX} = \vect{OX} - \vect{OP}</m>, then using the properties of the dot product yields
							 			<md>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\vect{PX}\cdot \vect{PX} 
								 				\amp =
								 				(\vect{OX} - \vect{OP})\cdot(\vect{OX} - \vect{OP})
								 			</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\amp =
								 				\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OX} - \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
								 				- \vect{OP}\cdot\vect{OX} + \vect{OP}\cdot\vect{OP}
								 			</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\amp =
								 				\norm{\vect{OX}}^2 + \norm{\vect{OP}}^2
								 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}.
								 			</mrow>
							 			</md>
							 			Similarly,
							 			<me>
							 				\vect{QX}\cdot \vect{QX} 
							 				=
							 				\norm{\vect{OX}}^2 + \norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 				.
							 			</me>
							 			So if we plug both of these into <xref ref="eq-1"/> and cancel the summand of <m>\norm{\vect{OX}}^2</m> on both sides, then we see that <m>\norm{\vect{PX}}= \norm{\vect{QX}}</m> is equivalent to
							 			<men xml:id="eq-reformulation-of-equidistant">
							 				\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 				=
							 				\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 				.
							 			</men>
							 			We compute with <m>X=(x_1,x_2,x_3)</m>:
							 			<md>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 					=
							 					2x_1 - x_2 + 3x_3
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 					=
							 					x_1 + x_2 - x_3
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 					=
							 					2^2 + (-1)^2 +3^2
							 					=
							 					14
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 					=
							 					1^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2
							 					=
							 					3,
							 				</mrow>
							 			</md>
							 			so that <xref ref="eq-reformulation-of-equidistant"/> becomes:
							 			<md>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\amp
								 				14
								 				- 2 (2x_1 - x_2 + 3x_3)
								 				=
								 				3
								 				- 2 (x_1 + x_2 - x_3)
								 			</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\iff \amp
								 				11
								 				=
								 				(- 2 x_1 - 2  x_2 + 2  x_3)
								 				+
								 				(4x_1 - 2x_2 + 6x_3)
							 				</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\iff \amp
								 				11
								 				=
								 				2x_1 - 4x_2 + 8x_3,
								 			</mrow>
							 			</md>
							 			<!-- the general form is correct; if a point satisfies it, then it is indeed equidistant to P and Q-->
							 			which is the general form of our plane equation. We can rewrite this to
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
												2\\
												-4\\
												8
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 \\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											11,
										</me>
										which is its normal form. Lastly, for the vector form, we need three points in the plane which do not lie on a line. Let us choose <m>R_1= (0, -3 , -\frac{1}{8} )</m>, <m>R_2= (\frac{3}{2}, 0, 1)</m>, and <m>R_3= (6,\frac{1}{4} ,0)</m> which all satisfy the general equation. Now, the plane's vector equation is given by
										<md>
											<mrow>
												\vec{x}
												\amp =
												\vect{OR_1}
												+
												t
												\vect{R_1 R_2}
												+
												s
												\vect{R_1 R_3}
											</mrow><mrow>
												\amp	=
												\begin{bmatrix}
													0 \\ -3 \\ -\frac{1}{8} 
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												t
												\begin{bmatrix}
													\frac{3}{2}  - 0 \\ 0 - (-3) \\ 1 - (-\frac{1}{8})
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												s
												\begin{bmatrix}
													6 - 0 \\ \frac{1}{4} - (-3) \\ 0 - (-\frac{1}{8})
												\end{bmatrix}
											</mrow><mrow>
												\amp =
												\begin{bmatrix}
													0 \\ -3 \\ -\frac{1}{8} 
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												t
												\begin{bmatrix}
													\frac{3}{2} \\ 3 \\ \frac{9}{8}
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												s
												\begin{bmatrix}
													6 \\ \frac{13}{4} \\ \frac{1}{8}
												\end{bmatrix}
											</mrow>
										</md>
										We can rewrite this by rescaling (<m>t=8r</m> and <m>s=8q</m>) to:
										<me>
											\vec{x}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
												0 \\ -3 \\ -\frac{1}{8} 
											\end{bmatrix}
											+
											r
											\begin{bmatrix}
												12 \\ 24 \\ 9
											\end{bmatrix}
											+
											q
											\begin{bmatrix}
												48 \\ 26 \\ 1
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me>.
									
							 		</solution>
							 		<answer>
							 			<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												2\\
												-4\\
												8
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 \\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											11
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											11
							 				=
							 				2x_1 - 4x_2 + 8x_3
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
											\vec{x}
											=
											\begin{bmatrix}
												0 \\ -3 \\ -\frac{1}{8} 
											\end{bmatrix}
											+
											r
											\begin{bmatrix}
												12 \\ 24 \\ 9
											\end{bmatrix}
											+
											q
											\begin{bmatrix}
												48 \\ 26 \\ 1
											\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
							 		</answer>
							 	</p>
						 	</li>
						 	<li>
						 		<p>Each point which is equidistant from <m>P=(0,1,-1)</m> and <m>Q=(2,-1,-3)</m>.</p>
						 		<p>
							 		<solution>
							 			A point <m>X</m> is equidistant from <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> if and only if 
							 			<me>
							 				\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 				=
							 				\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 				- 2 \vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 				,
							 			</me>
							 			see the argument in <xref ref="subex-plane-equidistant-to-two-points1"/>and <xref ref="eq-reformulation-of-equidistant"/> in particular.
							 			We compute with <m>X=(x_1,x_2,x_3)</m>:
							 			<md>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OP}
							 					=
							 					x_2 - x_3
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\vect{OX}\cdot\vect{OQ}
							 					=
							 					2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\norm{\vect{OP}}^2
							 					=
							 					0^2 + 1^2 +(-1)^2
							 					=
							 					2
							 				</mrow>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\norm{\vect{OQ}}^2
							 					=
							 					2^2 + (-1)^2 + (-3)^2
							 					=
							 					14,
							 				</mrow>
							 			</md>
							 			so that <xref ref="eq-reformulation-of-equidistant"/> becomes:
							 			<md>
							 				<mrow>
							 					\amp
								 				2
								 				- 2 (x_2 - x_3)
								 				=
								 				14
								 				- 2 (2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3)
								 			</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\iff \amp
								 				2 (2x_1 - x_2 - 3x_3)
								 				- 2 (x_2 - x_3)
								 				=
								 				12
							 				</mrow>
								 			<mrow>
								 				\iff \amp
								 				4x_1 - 4x_2 - 4x_3
								 				=
								 				12,
								 			</mrow>
							 			</md>
							 			<!-- the general form is correct; if a point satisfies it, then it is indeed equidistant to P and Q-->
							 			which is the general form of our plane equation. We can rewrite this to
							 			<me>
							 				\begin{bmatrix}
												4 \\ -4 \\ - 4
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 \\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											12,
										</me>
										which is its normal form. Lastly, for the vector form, we need three points in the plane which do not lie on a line. Let us choose <m>R_1= (3,0,0)</m>, <m>R_2= (0, -3, 0)</m>, and <m>R_3= (0,0,-3)</m> which all satisfy the general equation. Now, the plane's vector equation is given by
										<md>
											<mrow>
												\vec{x}
												\amp =
												\vect{OR_1}
												+
												t
												\vect{R_1 R_2}
												+
												s
												\vect{R_1 R_3}
											</mrow><mrow>
												\amp	=
												\begin{bmatrix}
													3\\0\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												t
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\-3\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												s
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\0\\-3
												\end{bmatrix}
											</mrow>.
										</md>
							 		</solution>
							 		<answer>
							 			<p>Normal form:</p>
					 					<p><me>
											\begin{bmatrix}
												4 \\ -4 \\ - 4
											\end{bmatrix}
											\cdot
											\begin{bmatrix}
												x_1 \\
												x_2 \\
												x_3 
											\end{bmatrix}
											=
											12
										</me></p>
										<p>General form:</p>
										<p><me>
											4x_1 - 4x_2 - 4x_3
								 				=
								 				12
										</me></p>
										<p>Vector form:</p>
										<p><me>
										\vec{x} = 												\begin{bmatrix}
													3\\0\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												t
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\-3\\0
												\end{bmatrix}
												+
												s
												\begin{bmatrix}
													-3\\0\\-3
												\end{bmatrix}
										</me></p>
							 		</answer>
							 	</p>
						 	</li>
						 </ol>		
						</statement>

					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.12.) </p></aside>
							In each case, calculate the distance from the point <m>P</m> to the line <m>\ell</m>, and find the point <m>Q</m> on <m>\ell</m> closest to <m>P</m>.
							<ol> 
								<li>	<m>P=(3,2,-1)</m>, <m>\ell \colon \vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}  </m>
								</li>
								<li>	<m>P=(1,-1,3)</m>, <m>\ell \colon \vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  </m>
							</li>
							</ol>  
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-dist-line-pt">
							If a line <m>\ell</m> is given by the vector equation
							<me>
								\vec{x}
								=
								\vec{a}
								+
								t\vec{d},
							</me>
							then the distance from <m>\ell</m> to a point <m>P</m> is given by
							<me>
								\operatorname{dist}
								(\ell, P) = 
								\norm{(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}) - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a})},
							</me>
							where <m>\vec{p}:=\vect{OP}</m> and <m>\operatorname{proj}</m> is as defined in <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>.
						</hint>
						<hint xml:id="hint-pt-on-line-closest-to-pt">
							If a line <m>\ell</m> is given by the vector equation
							<me>
								\vec{x}
								=
								\vec{a}
								+
								t\vec{d}
							</me>
							and <m>\vec{p}</m> is the position vector of a point <m>P</m>, then
							<me>
								\vec{q}
								:=
								\vec{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}),
							</me>
							is the position vector of the point <m>Q</m> on <m>\ell</m> which is closest to the point <m>P</m>.
						</hint>
						<solution>
							According to <xref ref="hint-dist-line-pt"/>, the formula for the distance between <m>\ell</m> and <m>P</m> is given by
							<me>
								\operatorname{dist}
								(\ell, P) = 
								\norm{(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}) - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a})},
							</me>
							where <m>\vec{a}</m> is a point on the line and <m>\mathbf{d}</m> is a direction vector of the line. We now only have to plug in the values for the two situations:
							<ol> 
								<li> 
								For the given <m>\ell</m>, we have
								<me>
									\vec{a} = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix},
									\vec{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix},
									\text{ and }
									\vec{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								</me>
								so that
								<me>
									\vec{v}
									:=
									\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 2\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								</me>
								We compute
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\mathbf{v} \cdot  \mathbf{d}
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix} \cdot \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp =
										\bigl(1\cdot 3 + 1 \cdot (-1) + (-4)\cdot (-2)\bigr)
										=10.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								and
								<me>
									\vec{d}\cdot \vec{d}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									3^2 + (-1)^2 + (-2)^2
									=
									14,
								</me>
								so that (using <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>)
								<me>
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\vec{d}\cdot \vec{v}}{\vec{d}\cdot \vec{d}}
									\right)
									\vec{d}
									=
									\tfrac{10}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								</me>
								Therefore,
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\ell, P) 
										\amp =
										\norm{\mathbf{v} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}}
										=
										\norm{
											\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ -4 \end{bmatrix}
											-
											\tfrac{10}{14}
											\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\norm{\tfrac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix} -16 \\ 24 \\ -36 \end{bmatrix}}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{ \left(\tfrac{-16}{14}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{24}{14}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{-36}{14}\right)^2}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{\tfrac{152}{14}}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								Next, for the point <m>Q</m> on <m>\ell</m> which has distance <m>\sqrt{\tfrac{152}{14}}</m> from <m>P</m>, we use <xref ref="hint-pt-on-line-closest-to-pt"/>: we need
								<me>
									\vec{q}
									:=
									\vec{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\vec{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} + \tfrac{10}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ -1\\ -2 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\tfrac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix} 58 \\ 4\\ 22 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								</me>
								so that <m>Q= (\tfrac{29}{7}, \tfrac{2}{7}, \tfrac{11}{7})</m>.
								</li>
								<li>
								<m>P=(1,-1,3)</m>, <m>\ell \colon \vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  </m>
								For the given <m>\ell</m>, we have
								<me>
									\vec{a} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix},
									\vec{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix},
									\text{ and }
									\vec{p} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								</me>
								so that
								<me>
									\vec{v}
									:=
									\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								</me>
								We compute
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\mathbf{v} \cdot  \mathbf{d}
										\amp =
										\begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix} 
										\cdot
										\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp =
										\bigl(0\cdot 3 + (-1) \cdot 1 + 4\cdot 4\bigr)
										=15.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								and
								<me>
									\vec{d}\cdot \vec{d}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									3^2 + 1^2 + 4^2
									=
									26,
								</me>
								so that (using <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>)
								<me>
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\vec{d}\cdot \vec{v}}{\vec{d}\cdot \vec{d}}
									\right)
									\vec{d}
									=
									\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									.
								</me>
								Therefore,
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\ell, P) 
										\amp =
										\norm{\mathbf{v} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\mathbf{v}}
										=
										\norm{
											\begin{bmatrix}  0 \\ -1\\ 4  \end{bmatrix}
											-
											\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
										}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\norm{\tfrac{1}{26}\begin{bmatrix} -45 \\ -41 \\ 44 \end{bmatrix}}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{ \left(\tfrac{-45}{26}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{-41}{26}\right)^2 + \left(\tfrac{44}{26}\right)^2}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp = 
										\sqrt{\tfrac{217}{26}}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								Next, for the point <m>Q</m> on <m>\ell</m> which has distance <m>\sqrt{\tfrac{217}{26}}</m> from <m>P</m>, we use <xref ref="hint-pt-on-line-closest-to-pt"/>: we need
								<me>
									\vec{q}
									:=
									\vec{a} + \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{d}}\vec{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}  1 \\ 0\\ -1  \end{bmatrix}
									+
									\tfrac{15}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
									=
									\tfrac{1}{26}\begin{bmatrix} 71 \\ 15\\ 34 \end{bmatrix}
									,
								</me>
								so that <m>Q= (\tfrac{71}{26}, \tfrac{15}{26}, \tfrac{34}{26})</m>.
							</li>
							</ol> 
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol> 
								<li> 
								<me>
									\operatorname{dist}
									(\ell, P) 
									=
									\sqrt{\tfrac{152}{14}}
									\text{ and }
									Q= (\tfrac{29}{7}, \tfrac{2}{7}, \tfrac{11}{7})
								</me>
								</li>
								<li>
								<me>
									\operatorname{dist}
									(\ell, P) 
									=
									\sqrt{\tfrac{217}{26}}
									\text{ and }
									Q= (\tfrac{71}{26}, \tfrac{15}{26}, \tfrac{34}{26})
								</me>
							</li>
							</ol> 
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.16.) </p></aside>
						 	In each case, find the shortest distance from the point <m>P</m> to the plane and find <m>Q</m> on the plane closest to <m>P</m>.
						 	<ol> 
						 		<li>	<m>P=(2,3,0)</m> and plane equation: <m>5x_1+x_2+x_3 =1</m>
						 		</li>
						 		<li>	<m>P=(3,1,-1)</m> and plane equation: <m>2x_1+x_2-x_3 =6</m>
						 	</li></ol>
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-dist-plane-pt">
							The distance from a plane <m>\mathcal{P}</m> to a point <m>P</m> is given by
							<me>
								\operatorname{dist}
								(\mathcal{P}, P) = 
								\norm{\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{p}-\mathbf{a})},
							</me>
							where <m>\vec{n}</m> is normal to the plane, <m>\vec{a}</m> is the position vector of any point on the plane, <m>\vec{p}:=\vect{OP}</m>, and <m>\operatorname{proj}</m> is as defined in <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>.>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							According to <xref ref="hint-dist-plane-pt"/>, we only need to find a point <m>A</m> on the plane and a normal vector <m>\vec{n}</m> to the plane.
							<ol> 
						 		<li> For the plane with general equation <m>5x_1+x_2+x_3 =1</m>, we can choose 
						 		<me>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}
									5\\
									1\\
									1
								\end{bmatrix}
								\text{ and }
									A = (1, -4, 0).
								</me>
								We then compute
								<me>
									\vec{v}
									:=
									\vect{OP}-\vect{OA}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										3\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}
										1\\
										-4\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										1\\
										7\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix},
								</me>
								so that 
								<me>
									\vec{n}
									\cdot
									\vec{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix}
										1\\
										7\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									5+7 = 12
								</me>
								and
								<me>
									\vec{n}
									\cdot
									\vec{n}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									25+1+1 = 27.
								</me>
								We can now compute (using <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>)
								<me>
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{v})
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\vec{n}\cdot \vec{v}}{\vec{n}\cdot \vec{n}}
									\right)
									\vec{n}
									=
									\frac{12}{27}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									\frac{4}{9}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
								</me>
								and thus
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\mathcal{P}, P)
										\amp
										= 
										\norm{\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v}}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp =
										\sqrt{
											\left(\frac{20}{9}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{4}{9}\right)^2
										}
										=
										\sqrt{
											\frac{16}{3}
										}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								The point on the plane which is closest to <m>P</m> then has the position vector
								<me>
									\vec{q}
									=
									\vect{OP} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										3\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix}
									-
									\frac{4}{9}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										5\\
										1\\
										1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									\frac{1}{9}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										-2 \\
										23\\
										-4
									\end{bmatrix},
								</me>
								so that <m> Q =(\frac{-2}{9},\frac{23}{9},\frac{-4}{9})</m>.
						 		</li>
						 		<li>For the plane with general equation <m>2x_1+x_2-x_3 =6</m>, we can choose 
						 		<me>\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix}
									2\\
									1\\
									-1
								\end{bmatrix}
								\text{ and }
									A = (3, 0, 0).
								</me>
								We then compute
								<me>
									\vec{v}
									:=
									\vect{OP}-\vect{OA}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										3\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									-
									\begin{bmatrix}
										3\\
										0\\
										0
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										0\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix},
								</me>
								so that 
								<me>
									\vec{n}
									\cdot
									\vec{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix}
										0\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									2
								</me>
								and
								<me>
									\vec{n}
									\cdot
									\vec{n}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									\cdot
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									4+1+1 = 6.
								</me>
								We can now compute (using <xref ref="def-proj-vect-onto-vect"/>)
								<me>
									\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}(\mathbf{v})
									=
									\left(
										\frac{\vec{n}\cdot \vec{v}}{\vec{n}\cdot \vec{n}}
									\right)
									\vec{n}
									=
									\frac{1}{3}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
								</me>
								and thus
								<md>
									<mrow>
										\operatorname{dist}
										(\mathcal{P}, P)
										\amp
										= 
										\norm{\operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v}}
									</mrow>
									<mrow>
										\amp =
										\sqrt{
											\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{-1}{3}\right)^2
										}
										=
										\sqrt{
											\frac{2}{3}
										}.
									</mrow>
								</md>
								The point on the plane which is closest to <m>P</m> then has the position vector
								<me>
									\vec{q}
									=
									\vect{OP} - \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}}\mathbf{v}
									=
									\begin{bmatrix}
										3\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									-
									\frac{1}{3}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										2\\
										1\\
										-1
									\end{bmatrix}
									=
									\frac{1}{3}
									\begin{bmatrix}
										7\\
										2\\
										-2
									\end{bmatrix}
								</me>
								so that <m> Q =(\frac{7}{3}, \frac{2}{3}, \frac{-2}{3})</m>.
						 	</li></ol>
						</solution>
						<answer>
						<ol>
							<li> 
								<m>
									\operatorname{dist}
									(\mathcal{P}, P)
									=
									\sqrt{
										\frac{16}{3}
									},
									Q =(\frac{-2}{9},\frac{23}{9},\frac{-4}{9})
								</m>.
					 		</li>
						 	<li>
						 		<m>
									\operatorname{dist}
									(\mathcal{P}, P)
									=
									\sqrt{
										\frac{2}{3}
									},
									Q =(\frac{7}{3}, \frac{2}{3}, \frac{-2}{3})
								</m>
						 	</li>
						 </ol>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 4.2, Exercise 4.2.23.) </p></aside>
							Find the shortest distance between the following pairs of parallel lines.
						 	<ol> 
						 		<li>	<m>\ell_1\colon\vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ -1\\ 3 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  </m> and 
						 		<m>\ell_2\colon\vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  </m>
						 		</li>
								<li>	<m>\ell_1\colon\vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 0\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}  </m> and 
						 	<m>\ell_1\colon\vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}  </m>
						 	</li></ol>  	
						</statement>
						<hint xml:id="hint-dist-parallel-lines">
							Find a plane <m>\mathcal{P}</m> to which <m>\ell_1</m> (and therefore also <m>\ell_2</m>) is orthogonal. In other words, the directional vector of <m>\ell_1</m> is normal to <m>\mathcal{P}</m>. Find the points <m>Q_1, Q_2</m> which <m>\mathcal{P}</m> has in common with <m>\ell_1</m> resp. <m>\ell_2</m>. What do you know about the line from <m>Q_1</m> to <m>Q_2</m>?
						</hint>
						<solution>
							We follow the idea of <xref ref="hint-dist-parallel-lines"/> and make one additional remark: The line from <m>Q_1</m> to <m>Q_2</m> is, by construction, contained in the plane since the two points are in the plane. In particular, said line is orthogonal to  <m>\ell_1</m> and  <m>\ell_2</m> and hence describes the direct path from <m>\ell_1</m> to <m>\ell_2</m>, meaning
							<me>
					 			\operatorname{dist} (\ell_1, \ell_2)
					 			=
					 			\norm{\vect{Q_1 Q_2}}.
					 		</me>
					 		We now follow this recipe for the two given pairs of lines.
							<ol> 
						 		<li> We choose the point <m>Q_1= (2 , -1, 3 ) </m> on <m>\ell_1</m> and the declare the directional vector <m>\vec{n}=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix} </m> of  <m>\ell_1</m> to be normal to the plane  <m>\mathcal{P}</m>. The normal form of  <m>\mathcal{P}</m> is then given by <m> \vec{n} \cdot \vec{x} = \vec{n} \cdot \vect{OQ_1}</m>, so its general form is
						 		<me>
						 			x_1 - x_2 + 4 x_3
						 			=
						 			15
						 			.
						 		</me>
						 		Next, we are looking for the intersection of <m>\mathcal{P}</m> with  <m>\ell_2</m>. In other words, we are looking for <m>t</m> such that <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> satisfies the general equation of  <m>\mathcal{P}</m>:
						 		<me>
						 			(1+t) - (0-t) + 4 (1+4t) = 15
						 			\iff
						 			t = \tfrac{5}{9}.
						 		</me>
						 		We conclude that the point <m>Q_2</m> that <m>\mathcal{P}</m> and <m>\ell_2</m> share is given by
						 		<me>
						 			\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0\\ 1 \end{bmatrix} +\tfrac{5}{9}\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ -1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}
						 			=\begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{14}{9} \\ -\tfrac{5}{9}\\ \tfrac{29}{9}\end{bmatrix} 
						 			.
						 		</me>
						 		The distance between the points <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> is then the distance between the lines:
						 		<md>
						 			<mrow>
						 			\operatorname{dist} (\ell_1, \ell_2)
						 			\amp=
						 			\norm{\vect{Q_1 Q_2}}
						 			</mrow>
						 			<mrow>
						 			\amp=
						 			\sqrt{(\tfrac{14}{9} -2)^2 + (-\tfrac{5}{9} +1)^2 + (\tfrac{29}{9} -3)^2}
						 			=
						 			\sqrt{\tfrac{36}{81}}
						 			=
						 			\tfrac{2}{3}.</mrow>
						 		</md>
						 		</li>
								<li>
						 			We choose the point <m>Q_1= (3 , 0, 2 ) </m> on <m>\ell_1</m> and the declare the directional vector <m>\vec{n}=\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} </m> of  <m>\ell_1</m>to be normal to the plane  <m>\mathcal{P}</m>. The normal form of  <m>\mathcal{P}</m> is then given by <m> \vec{n} \cdot \vec{x} = \vec{n} \cdot \vect{OQ_1}</m>, so its general form is
							 		<me>
							 			3x_1 + x_2 
							 			=
							 			9
							 			.
							 		</me>
							 		Next, we are looking for the intersection of <m>\mathcal{P}</m> with  <m>\ell_2</m>. In other words, we are looking for <m>t</m> such that <m>\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}</m> satisfies the general equation of  <m>\mathcal{P}</m>:
							 		<me>
							 			3(-1+3t) + (2+t)  = 9
							 			\iff
							 			t = 1.
							 		</me>
							 		We conclude that the point <m>Q_2</m> that <m>\mathcal{P}</m> and <m>\ell_2</m> share is given by
							 		<me>
							 			\begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2\\ 2 \end{bmatrix} +1\begin{bmatrix} 3 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix}
							 			=
										\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 3\\ 2 \end{bmatrix}
							 			.
							 		</me>
							 		The distance between the points <m>Q_1</m> and <m>Q_2</m> is then the distance between the lines:
							 		<md>
							 			<mrow>
							 			\operatorname{dist} (\ell_1, \ell_2)
							 			\amp=
							 			\norm{\vect{Q_1 Q_2}}
							 			</mrow>
							 			<mrow>
							 			\amp=
							 			\sqrt{(2-3)^2 + (3-0)^2 + (2-2)^2}
							 			=
							 			\sqrt{10}
							 			.</mrow>
							 		</md>


						 	</li></ol>  
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<ol> 
						 		<li>
									<me>
						 			\operatorname{dist} (\ell_1, \ell_2)
						 			=
						 			\tfrac{2}{3}.</me>
						 		</li>
						 		<li>
									<me>
						 			\operatorname{dist} (\ell_1, \ell_2)
						 			=
						 			\sqrt{10}.</me>
						 	</li></ol>  
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 3.2, Exercise 3.2.11.) </p></aside>
							Find the angle between the planes <m>\mathcal{P}_1\colon x_1+x_2=5</m> and <m>\mathcal{P}_2\colon 2x_1+x_2-x_3 =4</m>.  	
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Find a normal vector <m>\vec{n}_1</m> resp. <m>\vec{n}_2</m> for each of the planes. Using the <xref ref="cosine-formula">Cosine Formula</xref>, compute the angle <m>\theta=\sphericalangle (\vec{n}_1, \vec{n}_2)</m> between these vectors. Then,
							<me>
								\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}_1, \mathcal{P}_2)
								=
								\left\{
									\begin{array}{lc}
										\theta \amp \text{ if } 0 \leq \theta \leq \tfrac{\pi}{2}\\
										\pi - \theta \amp \text{ if } \tfrac{\pi}{2} \leq \theta \leq \pi \\
									\end{array}
								\right.
							</me>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							A normal vector to <m>\mathcal{P}_1</m> resp. <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m> is given by
							<me>
								\vec{n}_1
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ 0 \end{bmatrix} 
								\text{ resp. }
								\vec{n}_2
								=
								\begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1\\ -1 \end{bmatrix}
								.
							</me> 
							According to the <xref ref="cosine-formula">Cosine Formula</xref>, the angle between <m>\vec{n}_1</m> and <m>\vec{n}_2</m> is the number <m>\theta</m> that satisfies
							<me>
								\cos (\theta)
								=
								\frac{ \vec{n}_1\cdot \vec{n}_2}{ \norm{\vec{n}_1}\cdot \norm{\vec{n}_2}}
								,
							</me>
							so we compute:
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\vec{n}_1\cdot \vec{n}_2
									\amp =
									1\cdot 2 + 1\cdot 1 + 0\cdot (-1) = 3
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\norm{\vec{n}_1}
									\amp =
									\sqrt{ 1^2 + 1^2 + 0^2}
									=
									\sqrt{2}
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\norm{\vec{n}_1}
									\amp =
									\sqrt{ 2^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2}
									=
									\sqrt{6},
								</mrow>
							</md>
							so that
							<me>
								\cos (\theta)
								=
								\frac{ 3}{ \sqrt{2}\cdot \sqrt{6}}
								=
								\frac{ 3}{\sqrt{12}}
								,
								\text{ i.e. }
								\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}_1, \mathcal{P}_2)
								=
								\theta = \tfrac{\pi}{6}
								.
							</me>							
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<me>
								\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}_1, \mathcal{P}_2)
								= \tfrac{\pi}{6}
							</me>	
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

					<p><exercise><!-- xml:id="ex-" -->
						<statement>	<aside><p> (Source: <xref ref="ref-KN"/>, Section 3.2, Exercise 3.2.12.) </p></aside>
							Find the angle between the line 
							<me> 	\ell\colon \vec{x}  = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 3\\ 7 \end{bmatrix} +t\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}  </me> and <m>\mathcal{P}\colon 4x_1+7x_2+4x_3 =6</m>.  	
						</statement>
						<hint>
							Find a normal vector <m>\vec{n}</m> for <m>\mathcal{P}</m> and a directional vector <m>\vec{d}</m> of <m>\ell</m>. Compute <m>\theta=\sphericalangle (\vec{n}, \vec{d})</m> using the <xref ref="cosine-formula">Cosine Formula</xref>. Then
							<me>
								\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}, \ell)
								=
								\left\{
									\begin{array}{lc}
										\frac{\pi}{2}
										-
										\theta
										\amp \text{ if } 0 \leq \theta \leq \frac{\pi}{2}
										\\
										\theta
										-
										\frac{\pi}{2}
										\amp \text{ if } \frac{\pi}{2} \leq \theta \leq \pi
									\end{array}
									\right.
								.
							</me>
						</hint>
						<solution>
							A normal vector to the plane is given by
							<me>
								\vec{n} = \begin{bmatrix} 4 \\ 7\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}.
							</me>
							The angle <m>\theta</m> between this vector and the directional vector <m>\vec{d} = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 1\\ 4 \end{bmatrix}</m> of the line can be computed using the <xref ref="cosine-formula">Cosine Formula</xref>:
							<me>
								\cos (\theta)
								=
								\frac{ \vec{n} \cdot \vec{d}}{ \norm{\vec{n}}\cdot \norm{\vec{d}}}
								,
							</me>
							so we compute
							<md>
								<mrow>
									\vec{n}\cdot \vec{d}
									\amp =
									4\cdot 1 + 7\cdot 1 + 4\cdot 4
									=
									27
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\norm{\vec{n}}
									\amp =
									\sqrt{ 4^2 + 7^2 + 4^2}
									=
									\sqrt{81}
									=
									9
								</mrow>
								<mrow>
									\norm{\vec{d}}
									\amp =
									\sqrt{ 1^2 + 1^2 + 4^2}
									=
									\sqrt{18}
									=
									3\sqrt{2}.
								</mrow>
							</md>
							It follows that
							<me>
								\cos (\theta)
								=
								\frac{ 27}{ 9\cdot 3\sqrt{2}} = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
								,
								\text{ i.e. }
								\theta=\tfrac{\pi}{4}.
							</me>
							The angle <m>\alpha</m> between the line and the plane is then given by <m>\alpha = \tfrac{\pi}{2} - \theta = \tfrac{\pi}{4}.</m>
						</solution>
						<answer>
							<me>
								\sphericalangle (\mathcal{P}, \ell)
								=
								\tfrac{\pi}{4}
								.
							</me>
						</answer>
					</exercise></p>

